s of wind and solar, a maximum of half a day\u2019s average demand was needed for storage. In some areas of the grid, only around three hours might be needed.\nThis is an important point, because some renewable critics say that about a week\u2019s worth of storage is needed, and multiples of wind and solar capacity required for back up. These would be the same people that argue that climate science is a hoax, but it is a view that has more traction than it should.\nBQEND\n4 hours of storage would add just US$18/MWh to the cost of wind plus solar. And that's now: battery costs are halving every 3 years as we move down the learning curve. By the time we get to 100% renewables in 15 or 20 years, the additional cost of storage will be negligible.", "recommendation_count": "0", "in_reply_to": "115127239", "causal_relations": [{"cause": "the wind blows at night", "effect": "the need for storage drops to 6 hours"}, {"cause": "the grid can rely on existing back up", "effect": "that \u2019s built"}, {"cause": "some renewable critics say that about a week \u2019s worth of storage is needed", "effect": "this is an important point"}]}, {"id": "115112323", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1524664492000}, "author": "Virginia Stanley", "author_id": "16253111", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "PRis an old game. AT least the oil cos admit there is a problem.One would think that the solutions might be profitable but maybe the investment is too great. B P said it cleaned up the Gulf spill but of course that was a lie. Mankind is probably doo m ed for many reasons n s. MOST of those involve profits.", "recommendation_count": "3", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "115111666", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1524663510000}, "author": "vexjnovak", "author_id": "15391730", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "You don\u2019t need to be Sherlock Holmes to find this out. Either celebrities or researchers who are against fuel emission, \u201cchange\u201d their minds