ow-hanging fruit phase. There's no reasonable way that veganism can be seen to be in an \"exponential\" growth phase, particularly when veganism is not rigorously studied, and is known to be, for many, precisely a fad. Is a \"convert\" contributing to growth required to merely try it, or stick with it? And for how long? Where is the journalism in the Guardian?\nIn the global context, where expanding economies in Asia are massively increasing meat consumption in their diets, veganism as a panacea for global environmental harm is a lovely fantasy. But just as the article restricts itself to the prosperous, choice-enabled west, and a rather urban, exclusive, leisure and lifestyle focused sector at that where social media influencers can be cited as important, \u2026and where such choices might reasonably be, in many cases, seen as mere virtue-signalling\u2026well, I did not take much hope from the article. And not just because the supports it provides for its preposterous headline fall apart so easily, but also because real causes aren't supported by this kind of flimsy reporting.\nWhat I'd like to see are stories about people in China, or the rest of the Asian economies facing massive growth who are dealing with the issue. But that story would be hard to tell. And it would, perhaps, point out the deckchairs on the Titanic aspect of the individualistic veganism described. Yes, social media, as the article remarks more than once, makes it possible for ideas to spread and catch on, and that, as the election of Trump and the activities of Cambridge Analytica show, can be used in any way, including and perhaps especially in the interests of destructive incumbent behaviours that may become more extreme. Building veganism on social media evangelism is a double edged sword. \nAlso not addressed: what is the actual benefit to the earth and the individual in going reduced meat, vs vegetarian, vs vegan? I would speculate that it's the first term that holds the hope. Veganism is a modest improvement over vegetarianism which is a modest improvement over reduced meat consumption, but both with a greatly reduced chance of long term sustainability by the individual. If reduced meat can deliver 80% of the benefits within the less than 20% total global impact possible, but is twice as likely to succeed longterm, then that should be the focus. \nThe rest is vanity.", "recommendation_count": "50", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "114244701", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1522587353000}, "author": "Skipmeskip", "author_id": "12739257", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "I can remember becoming vegetarian as an 11 year old in the 70s, and being told I'd die (no kidding). So happy to see more and more people thinking about animals as more than items to be eaten.", "recommendation_count": "23", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "114244700", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1522587352000}, "author": "CaressOfSteel", "author_id": "2945349", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "Those people are vegans and are very healthy people. The claim was that it was impossible to have a healthy vegan diet.", "recommendation_count": "6", "in_reply_to": "114242083", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "114244699", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1522587351000}, "author": "actualff", "author_id": "12339176", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "Bullshit. The biggest argument for the acceptance of homosexuality was that it was not a choice, it was the way you were. Veganism is a choice. You are not born vegan, you are not going against your inherent nature by choosing ( or not choosing ) veganism. You grow up, and let people eat ( or not eat) meat as they choose", "recommendation_count": "46", "in_reply_to": "114239846", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "114244693", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1522587338000}, "author": "Danielle Thring", "author_id": "12554534", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "Nutritional scie