 global O2 levels. \nThere have been epochs where the northern latitudes have been tropical, and it was far from the end of the world. \nAnd let's not forget that in reality, we should be entering an Ice Age right around now... Who wants glaciers in NYC or London? \nFInally, most scientists agree to some fairly basic tenets, like the fact that the average temperature is increasing, although not at the predicted constant rate. I think most people think this is accurate as well. \nHowever saying that there is a '95% consensus' among scientists is both right and wrong. That may be true for a few basic assumptions or measurements, but it certainly isn't true for the models tossing out these predictions. \nHowever few scientists even mention that for one simple reason... funding. \nA climatologist who breaks ranks and openly discusses the various levels of uncertainty soon find themselves doing the nightly weather report on a TV station in Oklahoma, if they are lucky. \nScience tends to be an echo chamber, with the 'leaders in their field' defining everything from research priorities to grant levels. That's why almost every major breakthrough in scientific history comes from outside the established hierarchy. \nToday's scientific establishment is dedicated to supporting the concept of man-made climate change causing negative results because that's what pays the bills. Anything that might disrupt the funding for a branch of science that 20 years ago was large unheard of is ruthlessly suppressed from the inside. \nRather than looking at this group of people as 'deniers', we need to look at them as skeptics, something science always needs no matter how accepted a theory is. \nIn that light they are a positive thing, and a requirement for real scientists to work harder to prove it's hypothesis, or to be honest when they are disproven. \nAfter all, climate change is science, not faith.", "recommendation_count": "7", "causal_relations": [{"cause": null, "effect": "negative res