: "114437575", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1523033777000}, "author": "rockyrex", "author_id": "2923581", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "To add to WalkerRN's answer...\nThe Earth warmed out of the last glacial stage until around 9,000 years ago - initially due to astronomical cycles, but boosted by CO2 coming out of the warming oceans.\nThen the temperature was (nearly) stable for about 4,000 years - this is called the Mid-Holocene Climatic Optimum, or Mid-Holocene Warm Period.\nThen, about 5,000 years ago, it began to cool very very slowly - until humans began to add lots of CO2 to the air as the Industrial Revolution developed.\nThen it started to warm quickly, reversing the cooling trend.\nTemperatures at points in the Mid-Holocene Climatic Optimum might have been (just about) as warm as in the later 20th century, but only in the summer and only in the northern hemisphere.\nNow, in the early 21st century, the Earth is quite possibly warmer than any time since the Eemian interglacial over 115,000 years ago.\nThe Eemian was warmer than the Holocene because of higher insolation conditions.\nThe following graph is from data in this paper: \"A Reconstruction of Regional and Global Temperature for the Past 11,300 Years\" - Marcott et al, 2013\nhttp://farm9.staticflickr.com/8375/8579674565_c0fd53b616_c.jpg", "recommendation_count": "31", "in_reply_to": "114435816", "causal_relations": [{"cause": "higher insolation conditions", "effect": "the eemian was warmer than the holocene"}]}, {"id": "114437489", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1523033609000}, "author": "batsaintblind", "author_id": "15936671", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "Gaia theory is in for a very severe real-world stress test. Let's hope it holds up.", "recommendation_count": "0", "in_reply_to": "114405206", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "114437356", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1523033373000}, "author": "batsaintblind", "author_id": "15936671", "schema_org_type": "http: