hanges. \nNear where I grew up, on a drive we often took, was an island of beautiful forest set aside as state wayside. I remember this spot throughout my life and I was happy to introduce my son to this small, special spot that was largely unknown beyond the local area (very much unlike Walden Pond).\nBy the last time I visited the Douglas-firs were large second-growth trees and the big leaf maples formed a lush sub-canopy. Pacific dogwoods added unique flavor, as did the northern most California black oak I have ever found, and the cedars, in moist spots, added their swooping and drooping textural beauty to this lush green oasis surrounded by level farm field and defined by the road on the south. \nI could not put a price on how much this seemingly insignificant corner of land meant to me, and I know to others, and yet there was certainly a price that could be applied to the trees. I unfortunately do not mean in terms of soil health and retention, water quality and availability and also not in terms of carbon being held out of the atmosphere in lovely wood and soft, rich, warm smelling humus, and I don't mean in terms of providing crucial elements for diverse and complex living systems and lively communities. This is a global economy and the prices for timber, and fiber in general, is high.\nThe state parks system is hugely underfunded due to the \"tax revolts\" of the well healed.  Some years back there was a partial logging cut, but it was not too intense in the trees taken and the broader environmental impact. \nNow I have just come to find out that the land, or at least the timber, was sold to a logging company and the entire forest was cut. The pictures I saw were of a landscape I did recognize. I know in my logical mind that this is the same geographical spot that I visited so many times, but it is in no way the same place. It was shattered and exposed; it hurt me to see this and to think of how this could happen, why it could not be avoided and to think of 