perts in serious non-criminal cases. I recall a very senior judge saying that if the experts disagreed, he himself was in no position to decide whose opinion was the better.\nAs far as climate change is concerned, I think 'CAGW' is an unhelpful term, meaning the catastrophic bit. It allows people to say 'How big will this catastrophe be?' and then try to use the absence of a clear answer to undermine the case for AGW. I think the IPCC reports, as I gather second hand from apparently knowlegeable posters here and elsewhere, build in considerable uncertainty. Isn't this kind of uncertainty the very essence of solid science? As other posters suggest, 'proven' is not the right word. But no I don't agree with you either about gravity or AGW. They are both certain beyond reasonable doubt, although that term refers to the standard of proof in a criminal trial and seems inappropriate. I refer you to the paradigm concept, as Rocky Rex and others have often set it out here. We are in a period of normal, certain science in which details are being fleshed out, but main processes are not in any doubt at all. I don't agree that climate science has not applied scepticism to itself. Science IS scepticism, and AGW has been subjected to a phenomenal amount of scrutiny. Yes there are posters here who express themselves in florid language. That does not have much to do with sober science however. The consilience, coherence and consensus mean the science is indeed settled as some put it. We are not 'testing' anything by continuing to burn fossil fuel, we are inviting positively dangerous outcomes. The fact we don't know exactly how muuch and exactly when is a different point. I don't agree that 'the defenders' avoid discussing the uncertainties. Many thanks for the exchange - have to do the day job now.", "recommendation_count": "14", "in_reply_to": "114887669", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "114956080", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1524264511000}, "author": "GreenDementorCometh", "autho