2008\nIt took around 20 million years for CO2 levels to fall sufficiently for glaciation to begin in Antarctica, at the Eocene-Oligocene transition.\nAntarctic glacial inception began at around 750 ppm of CO2, and spread more widely as the CO2 level continued to fall.\nSo - eventually - if CO2 rises back to those levels (around 800 ppm) allowing for the fact that it takes a lot of (latent) heat to melt ice at zero C to water at zero C - this would create conditions where Antarctica would eventually become ice-free again.\nIt would not be quick, but reversing the process would be basically impossible - it would add 3 metres to sea level per century during the first millennium alone.", "recommendation_count": "11", "causal_relations": [{"cause": "which", "effect": "chemical weathering of rocks"}]}, {"id": "114856166", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1524049697000}, "author": "polytropic", "author_id": "16762123", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "The Guardian never gives two sides to any story. The Telegraph does occasionally.", "recommendation_count": "2", "in_reply_to": "114855666", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "114856014", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1524049449000}, "author": "zavaell", "author_id": "1347038", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "Go for it Jacinda - it's just a pity that we have a visionless woman as our PM.", "recommendation_count": "3", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "114854037", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1524045691000}, "author": "TheRedThreat", "author_id": "4019545", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "That's a hard one though. Being a resident of Japan, I have slightly differing views to most when it comes to nuclear being a 'clean' option.", "recommendation_count": "4", "in_reply_to": "114853057", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "114854017", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1524045657000}, "author": "John O'Donnell", "author_id": "12972318", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "t