2748", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "Nah lets give her a run in NZ and see how it pans out. We need to see the impact of these policies before we infect ourselves with the madness.\nWe have been having our own experiment going with SA and Vic. We see industry fleeing from SA due the renewables push sending SA from one of the cheapest places in Aus and the world for electricity, to the most expensive electricity in the world. Demand for power in SA is down approximately 17% since 2008, while prices have tripled. And that just generation costs, it has nothing to do with any gold plating of distribution, the price increase is soley due to the change in generation mix.\nRenewables do not produce cheap electricity to supply into the grid. AGL's own website clearly shows they cheapest generators by far are brown coal and black coal. Gas is much more expensive, and renewables even more expensive. And renewables force high cost gas into the generation mix to provide reliable power. \nhttps://www.agl.com.au/-/media/AGL/About-AGL/Documents/Media-Center/ASX-and-Media-Releases/AGL-FY18-Interim-Results-Market-Presentation.pdf?la=en&hash=D90B3F079A3A515A198DB794623A03BE9DB0EAE3\nhttps://www.agl.com.au/-/media/DLS/About-AGL/Documents/Investor-Centre/170317AmCham-Presentation-Final.pdf?la=en&hash=C826509280B7C28B4B0831E0E88C280B4F1FC540", "recommendation_count": "4", "in_reply_to": "114850528", "causal_relations": [{"cause": "the change in generation mix", "effect": "and that just generation costs has the price increase is soley"}]}, {"id": "114851906", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1524041581000}, "author": "arch54lg", "author_id": "3978770", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "It seems to me that part of the problem is capitalism and the need to maximise profits, often at the expense of the environment and the welfare of those on our planet. I wouldn't regard myself as left-wing by any means. Nor would I say I am an anti-capitalist. However, rampant capitalism is, to some extent to blame. It may be a necessary 'evil' in order for the planet and its nations to function, but we are producing more and more livestock clearly at a cost to the environment when, for example, alternative diets are available. Moreover we are transporting livestock (dead and alive) and other products further and further, again at a cost to the climate when, in fact, it would be perfectly possible to produce sufficient lower emission foodstuffs to feed our own nations if governments accepted the challenge and encouraged investment in the means to do so. Incentives to 'grow your own' would be a start. You only have to sit and watch the huge container ships coming into ports like Southampton and Felixstowe and the polluting effect of these, to wonder if there is another way. Unfortunately Brexit may well mean an increase in long-distance freight coming into Britain. \nWe also have to get freight off the roads and back on to the railways. Living in Kent I witness the fact daily of huge numbers of HGVs on our motorways, especially from cross-channel trade, while the carriage of freight through the channel tunnel in railfreight wagons is still relatively small. Switzerland actively encourages freight on to railways and most large manufacturing and distribution businesses are built close to, or by, railway lines so that factory to distribution centre traffic is largely rail-based. The Swiss are, by and large, conservative (with a small c), yet they have recognised the need for planning their infrastructure to reduce emissions. Meanwhile in Britain, rail electrification programmes have been scaled back in recent years as too costly and most businesses who used to have rail sidings have long since tarmacked over them. \nIt seems to me that governments have to intervene more and, to some extent, a mixed economy of command and capitalism is necessary. We have to accept perhaps that we will need to contribute by paying higher taxes in order for governments to be able to invest heavily in the technologies and infrastructure needed to reduce emissions. Maybe this also means disincentives to rear livestock that pollute more, while promoting through subsidies, those animals who are lower polluters than cattle.", "recommendation_count": "12", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "114851868", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1524041489000}, "author": "Grumblebum McWombat", "author_id": "17605685", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "BQSTART\nSince mankind started using fossil fuels our lives became a lot easier, fact.\nBQENDWelcome to the 18th century. Enjoy your stay.", "recommendation_count": "5", "in_reply_to": "114851799", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "114851799", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1524041342000}, "author": "Daniel Pye", "author_id": "12166228", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "Since mankind started using fossil fuels our lives became a lot easier, fact.\nEnjoy your bike rides to work and don't enjoy a holiday abroad this year if you really want to help your cause.", "recommendation_count": "8", "in_reply_to": "114851486", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "114851486", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1524040695000}, "author": "DennisHorne", "author_id": "4446531", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "Pye in the sky.\nMore CO2 more energy retained by Earth. More warming and less ice. Fact.", "recommendation_count": "9", "in_reply_to": "114851411", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "114851444", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1524040618000}, "author": "Grumblebum McWombat", "author_id": "17605685", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "Let me guess: you didn't read the whole article, did you?", "recommendation_count": "12", "in_reply_to": "114850049", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "114851429", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1524040587000}, "author": "seppowatcher", "author_id": "10592748", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "t