recommendation_count": "3", "in_reply_to": "114919726", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "114922270", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1524198733000}, "author": "Walsunda", "author_id": "12483673", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "\"2016 was an El Nino year with a lower than normal wet season...of course there would be more coral damage than 'normal'\".\nEl Nino and other ENSO phase years go roughly from the middle of one calendar year to the next. 2015-16 was a very strong El Nino year comparable in strength to the strong El Nino years of 1997-98 and 1982-83. However 2015-16 was hotter than those equally strong previous El Nino years because global warming had increased the climate and sea surface temperatures. So while very strong El Ninos bump up western Pacific sea surface temperatures for the year, that of 2015-16 was bumping it up from a higher climate temperature. \nThe bleaching event of 2015-16 occurred at the end of the Southern summer in March 2016. While some minor coral bleaching occurred in 1997-98, that of 2016 was the first mass coral bleaching event to be observed on the Great Barrier Reef. Large parts of the northern third of the Reef were bleached with high coral mortality within the following 12 months. \n2016-17 was a weak La Nina year with La Nina Southern Oscillation Indices for the second half of 2016 and just over the border into neutral SOIs for the first half of 2017. Nevertheless, in March of last year another mass coral bleaching event, of similar size to that of the previous year, occurred over the middle third of the Great Barrier Reef. \nThe mass coral bleaching events of 2016 and 2017 have produced more coral damage than was \"normal\" for similar previous very strong El Ninos and similar previous weak La Nina years.\n\"The reef is recovering pretty well at the moment.\"\nThe Reef is recovering slowly as it has been seen to do after damage from other sources (cyclones and starfish grazing). Such recovery has been observed to take up to 20 years.\nGlobal warming is increasing the frequency of extreme El Nino events from once every 20 years on average to once every ten years on average. Given the 20 years needed for recovery and the occurrence now of mass coral bleaching during weak La Nina years, this presents problems for long term recovery before the next bleaching event occurs in that area. There was overlap between the areas bleached in 2016 and 2017.", "recommendation_count": "3", "in_reply_to": "114881757", "causal_relations": [{"cause": "global warming had increased the climate and sea surface temperatures", "effect": "however 2015 16 was hotter than those equally strong previous el nino years"}]}, {"id": "114921933", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1524196019000}, "author": "greenveggie", "author_id": "12505139", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "Oh dear Kent!! You have no such science to back your claims so you attack it with unfounded nonsense.\nFor passers-by, here is an explanation of the peer-review process.\nWhat Kent prefers is a system where there are no checks and balances, no review by other experts - so basically, anyone can claim anything with no burden of proof. No qualifications or experience necessary. What could possibly go wrong?!", "recommendation_count": "3", "in_reply_to": "114887794", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "114921645", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1524192820000}, "author": "RJander", "author_id": "15758543", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "Warming by co2 is quantifiable and the radiative forcing has been measured. It seems to work as it should. What other explanation could there be. What makes it not so straight forward is that the heat is not evenly distributed. It mostly goes into the oceans and tends to come out during El Nino conditions. Ocean currents, jet streams and so forth make is so no place sees regular constant warming but a lot of variability with a warming trend.", "recommendation_count": "8