also requires CO2 levels to be quite low - in all the previous glacial stages of the Pleistocene \"ice age\", CO2 was under around 230 ppm.\nThis interesting paper -\n\"Determining the natural length of the current interglacial\" - Tzedakis et al, 2012\nreports that the end of the current interglacial would occur within the next 1500 years, if atmospheric CO2 concentrations did not exceed 240\u00b15\u2009ppmv.\nBut CO2 was already above 240 ppm before the Industrial Revolution.\nThis early higher CO2 concentration may be related to the development of agriculture, which disrupted the carbon cycle.\nClearance of forests for fields meant fewer trees, so less CO2 was removed from the air.\nPlus other agricultural activities, some producing CH4 (eg rice paddies)\nNow with CO2 over 400 ppm, the Earth is heading into conditions not seen for a very long time - way before modern humans were around.\nThose conditions are not conducive to glaciation.\nSo human activity has taken the Earth out of the repeated cycle of glacials and interglacials that has been going on for a couple of million years.", "recommendation_count": "7", "in_reply_to": "114999016", "causal_relations": [{"cause": "co2 levels", "effect": "warming"}]}, {"id": "115005122", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1524429281000}, "author": "John Samuel", "author_id": "13496713", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "You watch too much Star Wars. It's fiction.", "recommendation_count": "6", "in_reply_to": "115005039", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "115005039", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1524429039000}, "author": "rootmeansquare", "author_id": "100100977", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "Are you a Sith?", "recommendation_count": "3", "in_reply_to": "115004417", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "115004417", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1524427285000}, "author": "John Samuel", "author_id": "13496713", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "You didn't understand a word of 