way you will look for good anchoring points and good holds but the idea is not that these provide any ultimate position but they enable you to move on securely -\nthen of course as you approach your target point you will inevitably realise that the idea that this is any sort of ultimate destination is itself false and all that has happened is that new targets and new potential routes will appear.\nThe key point about all of this from the point of view of an observer, even if that person has expertise in other climbs or even if they are actually climbing a different route, we have no real choice but to accept the 'argument from authority' of what the conditions are what they can see ahead, of the people who are actually on the route.\nIt is not a question of blind faith, although of course inevitably there has to be a degree of faith that you are not in the grip of some elaborate practical joke or some such thing, \nbut that there is no better option that to accept that the reports coming back from the people actually climbing the route are the best guide you have to what in reality is happening, \nand if for every 100 reports you get back 97 tell you one thing and 3 tell you something different...?\nagain it would be insane to blithely assume that the 3 have the best view of the reality, particularly if this is based on nothing more concrete on fitting in with some old stories you have been told about what conditions are like over the top of the mountain.", "recommendation_count": "6", "causal_relations": [{"cause": null, "effect": "insuperable difficulties"}]}, {"id": "115199199", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1524906992000}, "author": "Anthonyhu", "author_id": "17407909", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "See above comments to Reinhard ...........", "recommendation_count": "0", "in_reply_to": "115198968", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "115208531", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1524927629000}, "author": "andy765gtr", "author_id": "17092002", "schema_